frameDefinitions: Geography as defined by its use.
This frame contains nouns denoting Aggregates of Individuals.
This frame has to do with people (the Residents) residing in Locations, sometimes with a Co-resident.
An Agent or Cause affects a Body_part of an Experiencer so that the quality of the Experiencer's perceptual experience of the Body_part is qualitatively changed.
A group of Colonists from a Homeland migrate to and proceed to settle in a New_area.
A Locale is characterized by the type of entity associated with the Locale.
frameExamples: You must land in the next <t><fex name='Locale'>airfield</fex></t>, as this one is currently having difficulties.
An <t><fex name='Agg'>army</fex></t> of postal workers descended on my office.
Chandra <t>massaged</t> Liliana's wrist because it was injured.
In the 7th century BC, Phoenicians <t>colonized</t> the eastern section of Libya.
This neighborhood started out as a Russian <t><fex name='loc'>enclave</fex></t>.
listRoleDefinitions: A stable bounded area.  It is typically the designation of the nouns of Locale-derived frames.
The activity that is carried out in the <fen>Locale</fen>.
This role identifies the people or things that form  the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
This role identifies the collection of entities that are the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
The individual(s) that reside at the <fen>Location</fen>.
The place in which somebody resides.
A person or group of people that the resident is staying with or among.
This role refers to the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Resident</fen> resides.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing a bodily experience in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> is the being or entity whose experience changes.
>The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s body where the bodily experience takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that affects the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s <fen>Body_part</fen>.
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the experience-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the bodily experience is caused.
A group of people who move together to an area outside their <fen>Homeland</fen> for the purpose of settling.
The <fen>Homeland</fen> is where the <fen>Colonists</fen> are originally from.
The <fen>Colonists</fen> move to the <fen>New_area</fen>, inhabiting it and (in the case of nation-states) extending the control of the <fen>Homeland</fen>.
The time at which the colonizing takes place.
A stable bounded area characterized by properties of the entities who are typically located there (e.g., work and/or live there).
A property or characteristic of the entities in the <fen>Locale</fen>.
listRoleExamples: There used to be a carnival every summer in that <fex><t>city</t></fex>.
The Campus <fex>Microscopy and Imaging</fex> Facility (CMIF) serves a wide range of faculty staff and students of The Ohio State University .
A crowd <fex>of hoodlums</fex> filled the plaza.
A <fex><t>crowd</t></fex> of hoodlums filled the plaza.
<fex>Spain</fex> settled the northern areas of Mexico through the use of missions, civil settlements, and presidios.
Norse invaders in the 900s colonized <fex>the North Midlands</fex> more densely than any other part of England'
A twenty-minute walk will take you to the Dutch-speaking <fex>quarter</fex> of the city.
A twenty-minute walk will take you to the <fex>Dutch-speaking</fex> quarter of the city.
